WEBVTT

00:02.320 --> 00:07.900
February 14, Valentine's Day, sitting in the 
basement of the Weissenbaker building, getting

00:08.040 --> 00:13.540
ready to interview Charlie Holland, who got here a 
little more than 50 years ago. Charlie, test your

00:13.620 --> 00:14.681
mic. Testing one, two. Is it all right? For

00:18.600 --> 00:28.570
someone who may not have known you in a few years to 
come when they're looking at this material or

00:18.600 --> 00:28.570
listening to it, would you begin by summarizing 
your background and experience, where you grew

00:28.790 --> 00:34.670
up, went to school, your experience before you got 
to Texas A&M? Well, I grew up in western North

00:38.530 --> 00:45.270
Carolina, and my dad was a Baptist minister. In 
fact, I started the first grade the year he

00:46.870 --> 00:53.650
finished Wake Forest. He had been in World War I, 
and he decided to go down and finish up. So we moved

00:58.950 --> 01:04.310
to Wake Forest, and about Christmas time, the 
twins were born, and he took me out. He took me out of

01:05.650 --> 01:10.550
the first grade, because he was afraid I might 
bring home some childhood diseases. And then the

01:11.970 --> 01:18.740
next year after that, we moved to Mountain View, 
and I was just recently at Christmas going up there

01:19.180 --> 01:23.320
looking for the place that we moved to. It was on a 
dirt road out from North Wilkesboro, and this will

01:27.320 --> 01:31.980
kind of give you the view of what things were like in 
those times. And he was pastor of a little Baptist

01:33.560 --> 01:36.360
church. There was a Baptist junior college high 
school, and he taught the mathematics there. And

01:42.140 --> 01:47.700
this was back in time that the Depression was 
coming on us out there. And all he got out of that

01:48.820 --> 01:53.480
year's teaching at that little junior college was 
an Underwood typewriter, which I have at home.

01:56.120 --> 01:57.161
That was all they could pay. And I went to school. It 
was a little one-room schoolhouse. First grade in

02:03.840 --> 02:05.980
the first row, second grade in the second. 
Pot-bellied stove. Down at the bottom on old slick

02:08.050 --> 02:11.130
red hill was an outhouse. And all the kids went to 
the outhouse. And also the water was simply a

02:13.290 --> 02:17.790
barrel, just like you'd see a keg of beer. And so Dad 
said, when we went there, I better put you back in

02:19.020 --> 02:24.320
the first grade, because I'm afraid I don't want 
you to get behind. So I started out in the first.

02:29.220 --> 02:33.440
Well, in that school, you could get promoted. All 
you had to do was just show you could do the second

02:34.260 --> 02:37.360
grade work. So before that... The year was over. I 
was over in the second grade, second row. They'd

02:41.340 --> 02:42.361
moved me to the second. So you just changed seats. 
You didn't know... No paperwork. Before the end of

02:46.300 --> 02:47.960
the year, I was in the third row. Well, then we moved 
to Stony Point, which is about 60 miles from

02:48.980 --> 02:53.820
Charlotte. And it's still very primitive in those 
days, but it did have a consolidated school. They

03:02.780 --> 03:05.700
bused all the kids from the county into that 
school. So Dad said, well, I know you were in the

03:06.400 --> 03:08.820
third. You were in the third grade there, but I 
think I'll put you back and let you do the second

03:08.800 --> 03:12.180
over. I don't want you to get behind. Well, they put 
me in that second grade, and I stayed the whole

03:13.860 --> 03:16.440
year, because they didn't know how to get me out of 
it, even though I knew it. Well, right after

03:19.760 --> 03:24.120
Christmas, we went back there and was looking for 
this. We wanted to go to all the places that we'd

03:24.220 --> 03:26.300
lived. And so we went to North Wilkesboro, and 
there was a bypass, and we stopped at a McDonald's.

03:32.070 --> 03:35.070
And this Mountain View wasn't even on the map yet. 
And so we went there to stop at a McDonald's. And I

03:39.120 --> 03:41.120
saw a well-dressed lady over there. And I went over 
and struck up a conversation with her. And I asked

03:45.380 --> 03:48.320
her if she knew where Mountain View was. She said, 
oh, it's just right up here. You turn off, right up

03:49.420 --> 03:51.001
the road here. Now, let me point out that in those 
years, Wilkes County was noted to be the biggest

03:54.140 --> 04:00.300
white lightning county in the United States. And 
so she said, yes. I said, I went to school there,

04:04.660 --> 04:09.320
one-room schoolhouse, outhouse down the bottom. 
I went to school in the middle of the mountain hill.

04:11.120 --> 04:13.520
And so then I went on back and sat down. And she came 
back over afterwards, and she told my daughter, or

04:13.520 --> 04:19.380
my sister, that her husband had passed away. And 
she says, well, what did he do? She says, oh, he was a

04:26.650 --> 04:28.091
bootlegger. That was the only way to make a living 
in those years. She said, well, didn't the law get

04:31.630 --> 04:33.530
after him? She said, oh, yes, he built time five 
different times. So this was kind of the, you know,

04:39.630 --> 04:42.130
the area that I grew up in. And my dad and I, he was 
always gone a lot and so forth. And we just didn't

04:50.240 --> 04:55.880
have these father-to-son talks that you always 
have nowadays or hear of, like Andy Hardy and Judge

04:55.860 --> 04:59.300
Stone. The closest we ever came to it was the day we 
were packing the car. He's getting ready to take me

05:03.980 --> 05:07.100
off to this little Baptist Junior College, Mars 
Hill, out from Nashville, North Carolina. And it

05:09.720 --> 05:14.880
was always assumed that I'd go to college. It was 
never even, we just didn't discuss it. And I

05:17.800 --> 05:22.040
delivered papers there, and I knew all the 
professional people in town. And they said,

05:22.120 --> 05:25.520
you've got, there's a lot of emphasis there on you 
need to, you need to go to college and make

05:25.720 --> 05:28.120
something yourself. You heard that over and over 
again. And so as we were packing the car, Dad said to

05:30.750 --> 05:34.960
me, he says, son, what are you going to study when 
you get up there? I said, well, Dad, I thought I'd

05:40.420 --> 05:42.100
study dentistry. He said, no, son, I don't think 
I'd do that if I were you. I don't believe you'll

05:45.340 --> 05:47.500
ever be able to keep up with your tools. Well, see, 
I'd lost his saw and hammer so many times that he was

05:48.240 --> 05:52.340
just, and he said, why don't you just go ahead and 
study engineering? Well, that's what I did. And so

05:56.800 --> 06:00.920
after the pre-engineering course up there, Mars 
Hill, I went to North Carolina State. And my junior

06:03.160 --> 06:07.940
year, I was having breakfast, and that's when 
Pearl Harbor hit. Actually, the day we were

06:08.380 --> 06:10.340
packing the car, the Germans marched in Europe, 
which marked the beginning, which is the day I

06:13.880 --> 06:15.501
started to college. And then when I was in my junior 
year at North Carolina State, the Germans, the

06:18.740 --> 06:21.440
Pearl Harbor occurred. So I went down, and I didn't 
want to get drafted. I wanted to finish school. So

06:26.700 --> 06:30.520
what I did was they had a program there where you 
could become, get a direct commission, even

06:31.100 --> 06:34.360
though you hadn't been in ROTC. They had an ROTC 
there, and people marched around all the time. And

06:37.640 --> 06:40.440
they told me I didn't need one point in taking. I 
didn't need one point in it, because I could only do

06:40.580 --> 06:43.480
two years of it. So I didn't take it. But I went down 
and got a direct commission to go in the Navy. And so

06:47.460 --> 06:50.600
as soon as I finished college, I had to go in the 
Navy. And I was in the Navy and on destroyers for

06:50.580 --> 06:54.600
about, just nearly four years was the tour date. 
And the roughest duty that we had was on Okinawa. We

07:01.580 --> 07:04.600
went up there with nine destroyers in the 
squadron. And this is where the kamikazes. And for

07:06.580 --> 07:08.600
about two or three months, we were exposed to 
kamikazes every single day. And we lost six out of

07:09.860 --> 07:14.880
our nine destroyers. There were only three of us 
that made it back. And it was just a matter of luck.

07:20.060 --> 07:21.081
We weren't that much better. And we just, when 
they'd hit one station, we'd be on another one. Or

07:25.060 --> 07:30.360
the plane that was coming in at you, we got it shot 
down. Well, then after the war, I thought about

07:30.340 --> 07:35.360
going to Georgia Tech, but it turned out that there 
was no housing down there. So I decided I'd work for

07:37.340 --> 07:39.360
Burlington Mills. And they had put me into a little 
program that was supposed to be training the plant

07:43.340 --> 07:46.360
managers of the future. Well, it turned out that it 
looked like I was going to have to work on the third

07:49.340 --> 07:52.360
shift for about 10 years, 15. So I decided I'd just 
go back to graduate school. I went back to North

07:55.340 --> 07:57.360
Carolina State. And Dr. Lindsey had taught down 
there. And so they gave me his name. I called him and

08:01.340 --> 08:04.360
came, got in touch with him. And so we came out here. 
And I began studying the graduate program. In

08:09.410 --> 08:13.430
chemical engineering in January of 1948. That's 
it. You came to Texas A&M? Texas A&M in January of

08:15.410 --> 08:17.430
1948. And I promised my wife, because we'd been out 
here when I was on the destroyer, I promised her

08:22.410 --> 08:25.430
we'd never stay in Texas. As soon as I got my degree, 
we were leaving. Well, we stayed. Still here.

08:29.410 --> 08:33.430
Describe what Texas A&M was physically. Okay. 
I'll give you the whole picture. I have some. A guy

08:39.240 --> 08:46.260
named Proctor was one of the first heads of the 
extension service, as I understand. And he was my

08:46.240 --> 08:55.120
brother-in-law's

08:46.240 --> 08:55.120
mother's father. He used to be over here in this 
same place of research. He used to have a picture

08:59.100 --> 09:01.120
over there. So we visited with the Lees on the way. 
And Mr. Lee had been taught. He'd been a high school

09:07.100 --> 09:09.120
principal. He'd gone to the old school and studied 
the Latin. He was a classical-type individual.

09:14.200 --> 09:16.220
And he said, so he called up Bolton. Bolton was the 
executive vice president. He said, get him a room,

09:18.200 --> 09:22.220
a place to stay up there. So after I'd already come 
here and gotten settled, I was over in Lindsey's

09:22.200 --> 09:26.220
office one day, and Mr. Bolton called up and he said 
he wanted to see me. Boy, they were just shaking

09:30.330 --> 09:32.350
over there. I went over. So he told me. But the 
amusing thing is, he ended up saying, well, just go

09:34.330 --> 09:38.350
over here. Oh, I'd forgotten. Boyette, go see him. 
He's in charge of housing. And that was what I got

09:44.680 --> 09:47.700
out of him. About a month or so, we were down there 
visiting with Mr. Lee again. He said, well, I

09:51.680 --> 09:56.370
suppose you know Bolton well by now. I said, I'm 
sorry, Mr. Lee. Our paths haven't crossed any

09:59.350 --> 10:02.370
since that one time I met him. But Dr. Lindsey was 
head of the chemical engineering department. We

10:06.350 --> 10:08.370
were over there in the old petroleum building. At 
that time, Barlow was dean of engineering. And

10:13.450 --> 10:18.880
Saul Wright was head of civil. Charlie Crawford 
was head of mechanical. Let's

10:22.020 --> 10:25.880
see. Shepard was dean of agriculture. Petroleum? 
No, petroleum. Harold Vance was head of

10:30.860 --> 10:32.880
petroleum. And Shepard was head of agriculture. 
And I don't remember. I remember Mr. Porter. Mr.

10:38.860 --> 10:41.880
Porter was head of the math department. But I don't 
know, don't remember now who was the science dean.

10:45.860 --> 10:49.880
I think Pearson was dean of the graduate college, 
followed later by Trotter. But Pearson, I

10:49.860 --> 10:51.880
believe, was the dean when I came here. I worked 
most of the time, dealt with Trotter's group over

10:51.860 --> 10:56.000
there. And I think that's, let's see, Street was 
teaching drawing. And I can't remember the fellow

11:01.300 --> 11:05.320
that was head of aero. And that's about the one. 
There were no sidewalks. It was all, actually, it

11:09.010 --> 11:13.030
was the same way it was in 1943. They had done 
nothing during the war. And what, I came in, we had

11:16.010 --> 11:20.030
already gotten over the flood here, but there's 
still a lot of veterans. And I would say that that

11:22.010 --> 11:26.380
was the toughest group to compete with I ever ran 
against because all they want to know is what's

11:26.360 --> 11:30.380
required, and we'll do it. Because you and your 
other veteran buddies, you were mentally,

11:30.360 --> 11:38.380
emotionally mature? Yes. And you were ready to go 
to work? Ready to go to work. You'd had experience?

11:42.360 --> 11:43.381
Mm-hmm. And also, you could separate. I had a 
family, too. Yeah. Everything was riding on it.

11:47.360 --> 11:51.380
What was your graduate student stipend or 
assistantship or what? Oh, it was probably about

11:51.360 --> 11:54.380
$100 a month. Right. And plus the GI Bill. I'm not 
even sure we got $100. Maybe we did. I don't

12:01.780 --> 12:02.801
remember what it was. But it was, living in College 
View, we could make it. But, see, by the time I got

12:04.780 --> 12:06.800
ready to finish, I ran out of there. Oh. I ran out of 
the, I took a job teaching. I ran out of the GI Bill.

12:13.030 --> 12:15.050
So I had to take a job teaching. And then I had to buy a 
house over in College Hills. And I bought one on

12:19.030 --> 12:21.050
Harrington Street over there. It cost $13,700. 
And that was the poorest year that I've ever

12:24.030 --> 12:30.530
experienced in my life. My salary was $370 a month. 
But Lindsay had to get special dispensation to get

12:36.610 --> 12:41.690
me $370. And so that's kind of what it was like here 
then. Now, when did you switch officially in

12:46.670 --> 12:52.690
paperwork from being a graduate student to being a 
faculty member? About 52. Okay. So you're, all

12:54.670 --> 12:57.690
right, we're still talking about the graduate 
student days. Yeah. Well, I finished, I got my PhD

12:58.670 --> 13:00.690
in 53. Oh, okay. But I'd already, I took a job as 
instructor in 52, I think it was. And then I believe

13:05.670 --> 13:16.970
in, I guess in 53, that fall I went ahead, I've 
forgotten whether I got promoted to assistant

13:16.950 --> 13:19.970
professor. Maybe I went a year before I got made 
assistant professor. Looking back now with the

13:23.950 --> 13:29.100
clear vision of hindsight, what courses and what 
teachers, instructors were the most important

13:29.080 --> 13:37.420
courses to you? Well, actually, we had some things 
back then and there that are better than they are

13:38.400 --> 13:43.520
now. And that is that we took courses outside the 
department, a lot of them. And I took mathematics,

13:48.500 --> 13:53.800
I had Luther, and I had Bayes. And then Dr. Klippel 
and I, years later, we worked on, I'd just go over

13:57.780 --> 14:00.800
with him and spend an hour a day, every once in a 
while, every week we'd have a meeting and prove

14:00.780 --> 14:04.800
theorems and so on. And chemistry, Jensen. And Dr. 
Watson. I worked under Murdock, Phil Murdock, in

14:09.940 --> 14:12.960
chemical engineering, but Watson was one of them. 
Another one that I took course over there was POTS,

14:14.940 --> 14:21.240
organic chemistry. And Kenny Hancock was another 
one that I took a course under. I also took a physics

14:26.260 --> 14:28.959
course, and Dr. Weeks taught it. And then after I 
finished my coursework, I went back and took

14:30.450 --> 14:33.470
another course in kinetic theory under Dr. 
Silvey, who goes way back. And old Dr. Silvey, the

14:39.090 --> 14:43.110
first day, there were three of us in there, 
registered for his course. And he, two physics

14:45.090 --> 14:49.140
students and me. And he said, he said, Mr. Tarlin, 
would you like to participate in the classroom

14:53.180 --> 14:56.680
discussion? And I said, well, I believe I'd like to 
do that. Well, what that amounted to, we were

15:00.660 --> 15:04.680
presenting one-third of that course for audit. 
And then I also had there one under Dr. Klippel, and

15:09.780 --> 15:10.976
I also had there one under Dr. Weeks over there. He 
was the first one. I took x-rays and

15:13.780 --> 15:16.800
crystallography, and I never had vectors. And he 
just, he had the course full of it, but I learned it,

15:19.780 --> 15:22.800
picked it up from him. And I had to compete against 
two graduate physics students in there, or three.

15:28.010 --> 15:33.480
And so Jensen was an outstanding chemistry 
teacher. Watson was an outstanding chemistry

15:33.460 --> 15:36.570
teacher. In fact, all of those people, he was never 
a real outstanding teacher. He had a tremendous

15:41.550 --> 15:44.570
amount of knowledge. But he could never finish one 
sentence until he started another one. Now, what

15:47.550 --> 15:50.570
was his first name? Because I remember Dr. Potts in 
agriculture. No, this was a different Potts. I

15:54.550 --> 15:55.571
don't remember what his first name is. You just 
have to look it up. What department? Chemistry. In

15:58.550 --> 15:59.571
the chemistry department. He was the organic prof 
in chemistry. Kenny Hancock taught a good course

16:01.550 --> 16:04.570
in chemistry. All right, what about within 
chemical engineering? Who were the key? Phil

16:08.550 --> 16:10.570
Murdock, I took a course under him. And

16:10.550 --> 16:14.280
let's see, you know, I may have taken most all the 
courses I took under him. I took one under G.L.

16:20.179 --> 16:20.280
Fair. He taught process control, and I took that. 
But we took, in those years, we were really taking,

16:26.380 --> 16:30.600
see, we didn't teach our own mathematics in our 
department. And now all these people trying to

16:30.580 --> 16:34.600
teach everything in one department, they never 
see the light of day outside the walls of their

16:34.580 --> 16:37.600
department. Did anybody, do you remember any 
advice that somebody gave you which later proved

16:42.580 --> 16:47.600
to be very valuable advice to a chemical engineer? 
Oh, I don't know. I just kind of stumbled along, I

16:51.020 --> 16:55.200
guess. I very nearly quit shortly after, about 
1955, because I went down to Exxon and worked one

17:00.180 --> 17:04.200
summer. And they wanted me to stay with Exxon. And 
at that time, I was making $5,000 a year, Dr. Harris

17:11.270 --> 17:15.520
was making $5,100 a year, and Dr. Lindsey was 
making $5,200 a year. And I was an assistant

17:17.500 --> 17:19.520
professor, and both of them were full. And I 
figured, well, why should I stay here when that's

17:24.260 --> 17:26.280
all I've got, that's all the future I've got? So it 
was, Shirley Lynch, incidentally, in that old

17:31.260 --> 17:34.480
building was head of geology over there. And 
that... What persuaded you to stay? Well, I just

17:40.350 --> 17:42.370
got to thinking about it that I don't know.

17:47.250 --> 17:49.810
What had happened was I had to hurry up and get 
through because that one year, Phil Murdock left

17:55.860 --> 17:57.880
and Watson left and all my committee left, so I 
really pushed that to get it completed. And I

18:04.020 --> 18:08.230
wasn't really sure whether I wanted to stay, I 
guess, in that corporate structure. You don't

18:10.210 --> 18:12.230
have near as much freedom as you do in the industry. 
What was your dissertation topic in your area of

18:16.210 --> 18:18.230
specialization? I'd done my master's on 
distillation, and this one was on catalytic,

18:22.210 --> 18:24.520
study of catalysts. And so on my committee, I had 
Dr. Potts from biology, or Potter, Potter from

18:33.300 --> 18:35.320
biology, and Dr. Weeks, and Dr. Watson, and Phil 
Murdock, were the ones on it. And I couldn't get it

18:44.100 --> 18:46.120
arranged for the final meeting, and I went by 
Watson's house one afternoon late, and he was

18:50.100 --> 18:52.120
sitting back in the backyard with his shirt off 
drinking beer. And I told him, I don't know if I'm

18:56.100 --> 18:58.120
going to be able to graduate this time because I 
can't get this committee together. Jordan said,

19:02.100 --> 19:04.120
Oh, I can take care of that for you. And he went in and 
called them up, and we met over in the old

19:08.100 --> 19:10.120
patrolling building that night. He set it up and we 
all met over there, and he said, Do you remember any

19:14.100 --> 19:16.310
special questions on that final oral exam? I don't 
remember. I just remember that they asked me some

19:22.290 --> 19:24.310
question, and I guess when you're working on some 
of those things you've got so many details in your

19:26.290 --> 19:28.310
mind and it's some little simple something you 
won't see. And they asked me that, and then they

19:34.380 --> 19:36.400
found the weakness. And so they just, I don't 
remember what it was, but then they just, I think it

19:42.480 --> 19:44.500
was, I think they just wanted to know what the 
problem was with the other, you know. And that part

19:50.480 --> 19:52.630
I remember. If you know it, let's go on to the next, 
you know, but if you ever find something that you

20:01.090 --> 20:03.110
didn't know. As you thought about it then and now 
look back, how did our chemical engineering

20:07.500 --> 20:09.840
department, how did our strength compare 
nationally in the mid-50s? Well, we got down

20:15.860 --> 20:18.130
because the salaries were so poor that at one time 
we were down to just Dr. Harris, Dr. Lindsey, and I.

20:26.620 --> 20:28.640
And we had to get some graduate students to help us 
out. So it was all we could do to even keep the doors

20:28.620 --> 20:30.640
open. You're saying three faculty? We got down to 
three faculty. Everybody quit because salaries,

20:36.620 --> 20:38.640
they went to industry or somewhere because 
salaries were so poor back in those days. And

20:40.620 --> 20:42.640
that's about when I was about ready to throw in the 
towel. But then where the real change come was when

20:46.750 --> 20:48.770
John Connolly got in there. Salaries went up, ours 
went up 30% a year. For three or four years there.

20:54.880 --> 20:56.900
But now let's back up. John Calhoun came here as 
dean in the 50s, didn't he? Marlow was dean when I

21:02.880 --> 21:04.900
came here. And then John Calhoun came next. Do you 
remember any early impressions of Calhoun as the

21:10.880 --> 21:13.800
dean? I just remember that he was much more 
energetic than well, Marlow was energetic enough

21:22.130 --> 21:24.150
except that I thought Calhoun was a much better 
individual than Marlow was. Did Calhoun did he

21:30.130 --> 21:32.150
come over and visit? Did he become acquainted with 
you all? Oh yeah, he had us over. He had me over to his

21:36.130 --> 21:38.150
office. And I think he was kind of leery of old Dr. 
Lindsey. And Doc had already told him, Calhoun

21:42.130 --> 21:44.150
told me he says, well here's my territory and over 
there's yours. Don't you get in here. Don't you

21:50.130 --> 21:52.150
come across this. But he did ask me one time. He had 
me in his office talking. I think I irritated him

21:56.130 --> 21:58.150
because he said to me, he said Calhoun. That's 
Calhoun. He wanted to know any disincentives or

22:08.640 --> 22:10.660
negative things about Lindsey. I said, well even 
if I had some I wouldn't tell you. So that ended that

22:16.640 --> 22:18.660
discussion. I may have hurt his feelings but I was 
pretty loyal to him. Old Doc did the best he could

22:24.640 --> 22:26.660
with what he had and he didn't have much to work 
with. Now the enrollment I'm assuming in

22:28.770 --> 22:30.790
engineering in the 50's was going up. Well no, 
actually what happened was the enrollment of

22:34.770 --> 22:36.790
everybody went down to about 1955 which was a low 
point. It was after the war was over and this was

22:40.770 --> 22:42.790
about in there somewhere maybe even after that 
they decided that they wanted to make it optional

22:44.770 --> 22:46.790
corps a little bit. And I think we went on that 
program for a little while and enrollment started

22:50.770 --> 22:52.790
going up. Then we went back to compulsory corps and 
it started going down again. So the enrollment

22:56.770 --> 22:58.790
never you could just do everything you wanted to 
and you couldn't end up with much more than two

23:00.770 --> 23:02.790
sections of about 20 some each. And you all still 
had the graduate program. Oh yeah. During those

23:08.800 --> 23:10.820
dry years. And I presume that industry was 
generally hiring the bright youngsters when they

23:15.090 --> 23:17.110
graduated Yeah, we had they were we were always 
able to place them and we helped place all those

23:23.090 --> 23:25.110
people. The only year that I couldn't get them 
placed was I believe in about 1980 when enrollment

23:31.250 --> 23:33.270
had just gone out of proportion and at the same time 
the job market dropped completely so we had a real

23:37.310 --> 23:39.330
problem then. Alright. But then Benson was after 
Calhoun Calhoun really wasn't Dean very long. He

23:47.980 --> 23:50.320
was up to what? Was he a system? He went up to vice 
presidential vice president for engineering I

23:54.430 --> 23:56.450
think. Right. When did you first meet Fred Benson? 
Well I met him before he became Dean. I knew him

24:04.980 --> 24:07.000
because we were both in a naval reserve unit 
together. And he wasn't very and we actually were

24:10.980 --> 24:13.000
taking one of the math courses there together at 
one time. He was taking one course, a lower one than

24:14.980 --> 24:17.000
I was taking. Did he do his degree here? Yeah he got 
his B.S. at Kansas and then he got a master's

24:23.140 --> 24:25.160
several years back at here as I recall and then he 
was taking some additional courses. Describe

24:31.140 --> 24:33.160
Fred Benson as a human being, as a personality. 
Well we got along just fine. One of the things when I

24:39.140 --> 24:41.160
got appointed what he did was call me in one 
afternoon and he said Charlie I'd like for you to

24:45.170 --> 24:47.190
take over here as head of the department. I said now 
you don't have to tell me right now. You can wait

24:51.710 --> 24:53.730
until a little later and tell me if you think it 
over. And so I did and I wasn't really sure I wanted

24:58.060 --> 25:00.080
to. I really wanted to tell him how about getting 
old Doc to take it one more year. I'd like to do the

25:04.130 --> 25:06.150
things I'm doing a little longer. But I decided to 
go ahead and take it because I thought that I could

25:10.130 --> 25:12.150
probably do more things that I wanted to do if I were 
head than I could if they got somebody from the

25:14.350 --> 25:16.370
outside and he started giving me all kinds of 
directions. When was that? What year? That was in

25:22.350 --> 25:24.370
1964. At that point you said things you wanted to 
do. What were your goals? I'd gone to Exxon in 55 and

25:32.350 --> 25:34.370
gotten started modeling doing distillation on 
computers and actually setting up programs to

25:40.350 --> 25:42.370
solve problems on them. And I worked with them, 
consulted with them and I had graduate students.

25:46.350 --> 25:48.370
We'd try out new methods and we had an old 650 and 
that's what they had at Exxon. And we had an old 650

25:52.350 --> 25:54.370
and they put it up in the old EE building. Now this is 
an old key punch? Yeah, in the building. And my

26:00.350 --> 26:02.370
graduate students would go up there and use it at 
night and it had a fire escape so they'd go up to the

26:04.350 --> 26:06.370
fire escape and run that thing all night long. 
That's what we did. That's the way we got our time.

26:10.640 --> 26:12.660
And we had a lot of that going on. I'd written a book 
and a good many papers on it. Methods that we had

26:14.640 --> 26:16.660
devised to solve these problems. So this was, at 
this point primarily petro-chemically related.

26:22.640 --> 26:24.660
Yeah. Or you can do chemical either one. It was, 
it's used in both fields. Not just one. But back to

26:34.860 --> 26:36.880
Benson. Describe him. What did he like and not 
like? How did he operate? Well, he I think although

26:45.470 --> 26:47.490
he would claim that he wanted everybody to say what 
they wanted to he really wanted to hear the right

26:51.470 --> 26:53.490
words. And he had around him people that he knew 
would always back him up. I remember I used to go in

26:57.470 --> 26:59.750
there to budget hearings. And he'd have Ed Fenner. 
Then he'd have Old Bain, Spencer and he'd have two

27:08.400 --> 27:10.420
or three others like that. And he'd say something 
and they'd all chime in. But he and I got along

27:16.590 --> 27:18.610
pretty well because I never did I never did go in and 
ask him any questions for me. I went ahead and

27:24.590 --> 27:26.740
solved the things. The only time he and I got 
crosswise was he was pushing real hard for this

27:31.260 --> 27:33.280
Doctor of Engineering program. And he had all of us 
department heads in there one day. And what he was

27:38.190 --> 27:40.210
wanting us to do was agree not to weaken down the 
B.S. degree to where it would not be an accredited

27:44.190 --> 27:46.210
degree and have the Doctor of Engineering be the 
first accredited degree. And I stood up against

27:50.190 --> 27:52.500
him because I told him that we could not afford to 
have a large group of students coming out of here

27:58.480 --> 28:00.500
without an accredited degree. If we were going to 
give a B.S. degree we'd better make it accredited.

28:04.960 --> 28:06.980
And he got so mad at me that he walked out and stayed 
gone for about 15 minutes. And then we finally

28:12.960 --> 28:14.980
decided we'd have it kind of optional. We'd always 
have the B.S. accredited. But if they wanted to go

28:21.380 --> 28:23.400
at an early stage somewhere over to the Doctor of 
Engineering they could. And so we'd just leave it

28:29.380 --> 28:31.400
where whichever one won out would be the way we'd 
go. And I told them we were just not big enough to

28:35.730 --> 28:37.750
fight against the whole United States on one 
program like that. They'd run us out of business.

28:41.730 --> 28:43.750
So he and I and then later he says Charlie you can do 
whatever you want to. But he told me many times that

28:49.730 --> 28:51.750
I had the best department in college engineering. 
How long in years was that Doctor of Engineering

28:55.730 --> 28:57.750
degree planned to be? Oh it was slightly longer I 
think than a Masters. And it was made up of course

29:01.730 --> 29:03.750
work plus a problem in industry. It was actually a 
real good degree. It might fit engineering better

29:09.730 --> 29:11.750
than some of the real because when you get over too 
far in the research you're nearly like a chemist or

29:13.730 --> 29:15.750
a physicist. And you could make a good program out 
of that where you would actually do research on

29:21.730 --> 29:23.750
things that pertain to engineering per se more 
than you can on some of the directions they're

29:27.730 --> 29:29.750
going in because they get toward the science end of 
it and then you're dealing with the physicist or

29:34.080 --> 29:36.100
the chemist and so on. So it was a good degree. It was 
just that I didn't think that we could swing it.

29:40.080 --> 29:42.100
What did happen to it? Well there's still I think 
they still give some of them but it just wasn't the

29:48.080 --> 29:50.100
demand for it. It's just hard to sell. So there was a 
key decision that I had something to do. I saved him

29:56.240 --> 29:58.260
there really. In Benson's personality did he 
laugh much? No he was always just in the meetings

30:04.240 --> 30:06.550
there was never much said. He got to the point 
pretty quickly didn't he? Oh yeah. And it was well

30:14.980 --> 30:17.000
thought out. Anything he did was well thought out. 
He was good to work for. I didn't have a bit of

30:21.170 --> 30:23.190
trouble working for him. We just had I mean he knew 
that I wasn't back down anymore. I'd express my

30:29.330 --> 30:30.208
opinion. He didn't like it but he respected it and 
then he told me later I think he really it hurt him

30:37.330 --> 30:39.350
that he couldn't handle it better than he did. In 
your early years as department head who were your

30:43.330 --> 30:45.350
key associates as department heads elsewhere in 
engineering and anywhere else? Oh well actually

30:53.330 --> 30:55.350
in those years I knew all the department heads real 
well. But who were the ones you worked with most?

30:59.330 --> 31:01.350
Well I knew Semang real well. He and I were well 
acquainted. Describe him. Well he was very

31:05.330 --> 31:07.350
precise and very fair and I had a lot of respect for 
him and he did for me. Describe him physically.

